TY  - JOUR
T1  - Organizational Roles and Transition to Entrepreneurship
AU  - Dobrev, Stanislav D.
AU  - Barnett, William P.
Y1  - 2005/06/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2005.17407910
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2005.17407910
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 433
EP  - 449
VL  - 48
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - How can one predict entrepreneurship, an individual's participation in the founding of a new organization? We propose that the organizational context of an individual either accelerates or retards the likelihood of entrepreneurship, depending on the individual's role in the organization. The effects of role hinge, we argue, on the founder's charismatic identity, and the decoupling of this identity from the organization as it ages and grows. Our findings support the proposition that organizational properties that affect the likelihood of becoming an entrepreneur do so in opposite ways for organizational members and founders. We discuss how our theory and results demonstrate the value of a sociological perspective on entrepreneurship.
AB  - How can one predict entrepreneurship, an individual's participation in the founding of a new organization? We propose that the organizational context of an individual either accelerates or retards the likelihood of entrepreneurship, depending on the individual's role in the organization. The effects of role hinge, we argue, on the founder's charismatic identity, and the decoupling of this identity from the organization as it ages and grows. Our findings support the proposition that organizational properties that affect the likelihood of becoming an entrepreneur do so in opposite ways for organizational members and founders. We discuss how our theory and results demonstrate the value of a sociological perspective on entrepreneurship.
